# Port Layer Architecture

**Before writing any code here, read all of the following:**

- `docs/architecture/integrations.md` — port–adapter design principles P1–P6
- `docs/architecture/quality-and-delivery.md` — fake-before-merge requirement
- `docs/adr/ADR-004-domain-contracts-pydantic.md` — why data contracts live in `src/domain/`

## Spec-first workflow

Check for an existing spec in `docs/specs/ports/<port-slug>-spec.md` before writing anything.
Specs are authored by humans by default. Only draft a spec from
`docs/specs/templates/port-spec-template.md` if the human explicitly asks you to, and wait
for approval before saving it or writing any code.

## Non-negotiable constraints

**Structural typing — use `Protocol`, not ABC**
Define every port as a `typing.Protocol`. Adapters satisfy it structurally — no explicit
inheritance required (P4). The type checker enforces conformance at usage sites.

```python
# src/ports/llm.py
from typing import Protocol
from src.domain import LlmRequest, LlmResponse

class LlmPort(Protocol):
    def invoke(self, request: LlmRequest) -> LlmResponse:
        """Generate a completion for the given request."""
        ...
```

**Domain intent only — no vendor details on the interface (P3)**
Port method signatures express what the domain needs. Technology-specific parameters
(connection strings, pagination cursors, retry hints, SDK flags) must not appear on a port.
If a parameter would not appear in a business requirements document, it does not belong here.

**Data contracts in `src/domain/`, not in `src/ports/` (P2)**
Ports define behavioral contracts. Shared types — Pydantic models, enums, typed errors —
belong in `src/domain/`. Ports may import from `src/domain/`; ports must never import from
`src/adapters/` or from each other.

**One port per external capability**
Add a new port only when adding a genuinely new external capability. Do not overload an
existing port with unrelated methods.

**Fake required before merge (P5)**
Every new port must ship with a matching fake in `tests/fakes/` in the same PR.
The fake must be a working in-memory implementation of the Protocol — not a mock.
